metadata.name: Seriscope Painting (2) #8
metadata.description:
Seriscope Paintings are composed via a generative printing process similar to serigraphy (silkscreen). A number of abstract paintings were produced traditionally using a paper marbling technique and used as a dataset to combine 4 single-colour halftone layers to make the image.

Seriscope paintings are generatively composed from a selection of:

40 Background (Who) Paintings
61 Midground (What) Paintings
61 Midground (Where) Paintings
81 Foreground (Why) Paintings

The title of each painting is also generatively composed at the time of mint within the attributes of the work - who, what, where and why.

Ryan Thompson, Jan 2022
@RT_Artwork

metadata.name: Crescimento #2
winter trees #62
metadata.description:
I once took an Amtrak train from New York City to Portland, Oregon in the winter. This seemed like it would be exciting. It was not. However, one moonlit night in North Dakota, I was gazing out the window and saw a small clump of trees, with the full moon over them. I quickly snapped a picture, which I still have, and which is my fondest memory of this trip. This is a recreation of this image in generative code. 

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: FairyCells #195
metadata.description:
FairyCells is a series created by a generative system, displaying shapes, between 1 and 10, made up of three different color palettes. 
Cells cannot cross each other, and are composed of a flat tint and/or a hatch system.

You can right-click to download an SVG file of the NFT or press « E » to export as png (3401x3401px)

Moreover, the digital version can exist as a physical piece.
Owning the NFT gives the right to order, in addition, a 30x30cm plotter drawing of it. More information about it here: https://nft.julienespagnon.fr/fairy-cells.
You can see some test examples plotted in the google form: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1FO3Umh49qmJApZAlQgZ46a2y421QYEWIW8r72nLrW4Q/edit

Work by Julien Espagnon - 2021/2022

metadata.name: Mei(梅) #149
metadata.description:
Mei(梅):

"Mei" is an oriental art piece featuring the imagery of plum blossom, a symbol of courage and perseverance in traditional Chinese culture.

The generative system at the backend of "Mei" is an exploration of this cultural symbol by modern art language. The basic elements of the paintings are merely circles and enclosed flow field shapes. A great variety of short and light strokes of such elements are used across the paintings. Xuan paper is occasionally used as background, which is a painting material since the Tang dynasty.

Mei's outputs span different stages of plum blossom from winter to spring. The scene also changes from a calm day to snowy or even stormy weather. The consistent yet complex senses and feelings reflected are surprisingly versatile.

metadata.name: Visa to the stars #87
metadata.description:
Generative space scenes with an illustrative look.

Use the capture functions to export in big after opening it in its own window, the artwork is full of details.

Press SPACE to show/hide the menu

Control the camera and explore the scene with :
- Mouse Left : Rotate
- Mouse Right : Pan
- Mouse Middle : Zoom

I wrote an article about the project, with a technical breakdown of the piece at https://ulucode.com/wp/visa-to-the-stars/


Decent GPU REQUIRED, you can tune the performances with the "Quality" setting in the menu.
Better performances with Chrome.

Keyboard shortcuts:
SPACE : show/hide menu
A : toggle anti-aliasing
C : take a capture of the ccurrently selected resolution
R : reset camera position/orientation
S : display stats
P : pause animation

metadata.name: Refractions #202
metadata.description:
Refractions is a study of frequencies, harmonies and abstract representations of natural phenomena. 

It is an experiment of blending three colors to create integrated textural compositions.


Probabilities;

- 14 compositions with variations.

- 2 background color.

- 19 different base color palette (2 monochrome).

- 2 distinct textures with variations.

-  2 different alpha types; tangential & sinusoidal.

- Different edges.

- Several starting positions and styles (wavy or straight).


Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, April 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Abstract Sunset #6
metadata.description:
The AI sees the sunset 20 times in a day. One loves the sunset, when one is so sad.

Never in history have we been so dependent on machines. I also think art should keep up with AI as it evolves. So when I ask an AI to draw up abstract sunsets for 20 times, what will it see? And can I collaborate with it to make it more organic?

Technical Notes: OpenAI's GLIDE model, with prompt “an abstract painting of a sunset” that turned the text into images for 20 time, each took about 20 minutes on a macbook pro. Then based on the output, I used the Floyd-Steinberg Dithering technique to calculate the values to be painted. Finally I tuned the strokes and landed on using giant circles (the edges of these circles to be exact) to paint for a more organic feel.
